04676nam a22006015i 9780822386056DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20042004ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1229161575  a97808223860567 a10.1515/97808223860562doi  a(DE-B1597)553535  a(OCoLC)1226680157  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aN7399.S4bH37 2004 7aART0150102bisacsh04a709/.663/090452221 aHarney, Elizabeth, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIn Senghor's Shadow :bArt, Politics, and the Avant-Garde in Senegal, 1960–1995 /cElizabeth Harney; ed. by Nicholas Thomas. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2004] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (360 p.) :b14 color photos, 78 b&w photos  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aObjects/Histories : 1700tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- t1 Rhythm as the Architecture of Being: Reflections on un Âme Nègre -- t2 The École de Dakar: Pan-Africanism in Paint and Textile -- t3 Laboratories of Avant-Gardism -- t4 After the Avant-Garde -- t5 Passport to the Global Art World -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Senghor’s Shadow is a unique study of modern art in postindependence Senegal. Elizabeth Harney examines the art that flourished during the administration of Léopold Sédar Senghor, Senegal’s first president, and in the decades since he stepped down in 1980. As a major philosopher and poet of Negritude, Senghor envisioned an active and revolutionary role for modern artists, and he created a well-funded system for nurturing their work. In questioning the canon of art produced under his aegis—known as the Ecole de Dakar—Harney reconsiders Senghor’s Negritude philosophy, his desire to express Senegal’s postcolonial national identity through art, and the system of art schools and exhibits he developed. She expands scholarship on global modernisms by highlighting the distinctive cultural history that shaped Senegalese modernism and the complex and often contradictory choices made by its early artists.Heavily illustrated with nearly one hundred images, including some in color, In Senghor’s Shadow surveys the work of a range of Senegalese artists, including painters, muralists, sculptors, and performance-based groups—from those who worked at the height of Senghor’s patronage system to those who graduated from art school in the early 1990s. Harney reveals how, in the 1970s, avant-gardists contested Negritude beliefs by breaking out of established artistic forms. During the 1980s and 1990s, artists such as Moustapha Dimé, Germaine Anta Gaye, and Kan-Si engaged with avant-garde methods and local artistic forms to challenge both Senghor’s legacy and the broader art world’s understandings of cultural syncretism. Ultimately, Harney’s work illuminates the production and reception of modern Senegalese art within the global arena.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aArt and statezSenegal. 0aAvant-garde (Aesthetics)zSenegalzDakarxHistoryy20th century. 0aModernism (Art)zSenegalzDakar. 0aNegritude (Literary movement)zSenegalxInfluence. 7aART / African.2bisacsh1 aThomas, Nicholas, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822386056zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822386056423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780822386056/original  a978-3-11-071183-7  Duke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_AL